<Layout title="Color scheme (CSS)" maturity="budding">
<p>
    A CSS color scheme for a website can be stored in CSS variables.
    Usually the variables for the color scheme are stored in the <code>:root</code> pseudo-class:
</p>
<pre><code is:raw>:root {
    --color-text: black;
    --color-base: white;
}
</code></pre>
<p>Now everywhere in the CSS the text color can be accessed with <code>var(--color-text)</code>.
<h2>Color scheme based on browser preference</h2>
<p>
    Users express their preference by toggling light or dark mode (or follow OS preference) in the browser settings.
    The <code>prefers-color-scheme</code> CSS media feature is used to detect if a light or dark color scheme is preferred<sup><a href="#footnote-1">[1]</a></sup>.
    The media feature can be leveraged to overwrite the CSS variables that store the color scheme colors:
</p>
<pre><code is:raw>@media (prefers-color-scheme:dark) {
    :root {
        --color-text: white;
        --color-base: black;
    }
}
</code></pre>

<hr>
<ul>
    <li>
        This is explained in detail at the
        <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@media/prefers-color-scheme">MDN web docs</a>.
    </li>
</ul>
</Layout>
